The function can utilize dynamic programming to build a 2D matrix where each cell stores the length of the longest common substring ending at the corresponding positions in the input strings.

```python
def longest_common_substring_len(a, b):
    m, n = len(a), len(b)
    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]
    max_len = 0
    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            if a[i - 1] == b[j - 1]:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1
                max_len = max(max_len, dp[i][j])
    return max_len
